'''YourMechanic''' is a privately held startup company based in [[Mountain View, California]].<ref name="Kokalitcheva 2016"/><ref name="Naughton 2016">{{cite web | last=Naughton | first=Nora | title=Competition in the palm of your customer's hands | website=[[Automotive News]] | date=February 15, 2016 | url=http://www.autonews.com/article/20160215/RETAIL05/302159964/competition-in-the-palm-of-your-customers-hands | accessdate=March 7, 2017}}</ref> The company provides mobile car repair and maintenance services to car owners at their location (home or office).<ref>Temple, James and Evangelista, Benny (September 11, 2012).[http://www.sfgate.com/technology/article/Mayor-declares-Innovation-Month-in-S-F-3857562.php#page-2 “Mayor declares Innovation Month in San Francisco”]. ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]''. Retrieved March 25, 2015.</ref><ref name="Naughton 2016"/>
The company currently operates in over 700 cities within 50+ major metro areas in the United States.<ref>[https://www.yourmechanic.com YourMechanic]</ref> Services are performed by certified mechanics.<ref name="Mitroff 2012">{{cite web | last=Mitroff | first=Sarah | title=A $2M Deal for Mechanics on Wheels | website=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] | date=September 13, 2012 | url=https://www.wired.com/2012/09/yourmechanic/ | accessdate=March 7, 2017}}</ref>

The company has raised $32 million to date, most recently with $24 million<ref name="Kokalitcheva 2016">{{cite web | author=Kokalitcheva, Kia |title=Why This Startup for Car Repair House Calls Chose to Grow Slowly | website=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] | date=February 1, 2016 | url=http://fortune.com/2016/03/01/yourmechanic-24-million/ | accessdate=March 7, 2017}}</ref> provided by SoftBank Capital, Lerer Hippeau Ventures, Data Point Capital, Andreessen Horowitz, SAIC, Verizon Ventures, American Family Insurance, PG Ventures, Promus Ventures, and Silicon Valley Bank.

Most mechanics are certified by National Institute for Automotive Service Excellence (ASE) and some are certified by similar organizations and/or have dealer or factory training. A new customer can review mechanics’ certifications during the booking process in addition to experience, work history, jobs completed for other car owners, fees paid by other car owners, and customers ratings and reviews. Mechanics undergo background checks and other screenings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yourmechanic.com/support|title=Contact Us|website=YourMechanic|access-date=2016-09-29}}</ref>

The company has a [[mobile app]] that provides consumers a means to obtain price quotes and schedule repairs and services.<ref>{{cite web | last=Hall-Geisler | first=Kristen | title=The coolest tech at the LA Auto Show | website=[[Popular Science]] | date=November 29, 2016 | url=http://www.popsci.com/top-tech-from-los-angeles-auto-show | accessdate=March 7, 2017}}</ref>

==History==

In 2012, Art Agrawal (Co-founder) and Dongyi Liao (CTO) founded YourMechanic.

In September 2012, the company raised $1.8 million in seed funding from venture firms and investors including [[Andreessen Horowitz]], SV Angel, Crunch Fund, Promus Ventures, [[Greylock Partners]], DFJ, Lerer Ventures, PG Ventures, [[Ashton Kutcher]], [[Jawed Karim]], Dave Gilboa, [[Justin Waldron]], [[Joshua Schachter]], Hector Hulian, Paige Craig, Mark Friedgan, Alex Goldstein, Sam Angus, [[Slide.com|Kevin Freedman]], Jeremy Wenokur and Rob Wang.<ref>Lawler, Ryan (December 17, 2013). [https://techcrunch.com/2013/12/17/yourmechanic-iphone-app/ “YourMechanic Launches An iPhone App To Connect You With A Mechanic While On The Go“]. [[TechCrunch]]. Retrieved April 16, 2015.</ref>

In September 2012, the company won the [[TechCrunch#TechCrunch Disrupt|TechCrunch Battlefield Disrupt San Francisco]] competition against other finalists Saya, [[Lit Motors]], Prior Knowledge, Zumper, Gyft and [[Expert Labs]].<ref>Samuels, Diana (September 11, 2012). [http://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/blog/2012/09/startup-yourmechanic-is-a-car-mechanic.html “Startup YourMechanic is a car mechanic that makes house calls”]. [[Silicon Valley Business Journal]]. Retrieved March 25, 2015.</ref>

In March 2016, the company announced $24 million in funding, bringing its total funding to $32 million.<ref name="Kokalitcheva 2016"/>

